Identify Color Contrast Issues with Color Contrast Analyzer & Chrome DevTools

01
On this page
  1. Find Your Contrast Target
    1. Determining Computed Font Size
  2. Measuring Color Contrast Ratio
  3. Shortcomings of DevTools Contrast Checking
  4. Colour Contrast Analyzer (CCA)
  5. 🛠 Challenge: Fix MegaNav Contrast Issues
    1. 🛠 Solution: Updating MegaNav Contrast issues

Take a look at the gray-on-gray color scheme in the navigation menu.

You might be able to tell without using a tool that there's not a lot of contrast between the text and highlight color in the nav.

Sometimes contrast might appear to be close enough to a passing ratio for foreground and background colors, but isn't quite there.

Find Your Contrast Target

In order to fulfill the minimum contrast guidelines set by WCAG 2.2, the contrast ratio for plain text needs to be at least 4.5:1 (read as “four point five to one”).

For "large scale" text (size 18 point), the WCAG guideline is a contrast ratio of 3:1. In terms of pixels, your text counts as large if it’s at least 24 pixels.

Determining Computed Font Size

The “Computed” pane in Chrome DevTools displays details about the currently selected element.

Inspect the “Plan Your Trip” button in the MegaNav, then open the Computed pane and scroll to the font-size entry.

Because the MegaNav’s computed font size is 14.4px, it qualifies as “regular text” which means the required contrast ratio is 4.5:1.

Measuring Color Contrast Ratio

You don't have to worry about calculating the ratio yourself.

There are quite a few tools we can use to check color contrast to meet these guidelines.

In Chrome DevTools, clicking a color preview box in the Styles pane will open a color picker that often shows the current contrast ratio. In this case, the current menu button text color set by the color-accent-mediumdark variable has a contrast ratio of only 3.27.

Expanding the contrast ratio dropdown on the color picker will show you some contrast ratio lines to help you pick a new color.

When you find one that meets AA or AAA guidelines, green checkmarks will appear. Note that the element you’re choosing a color will live update as you move the color picker.

Shortcomings of DevTools Contrast Checking

While the contrast tool built into Chrome DevTools is useful, there are some shortcomings.

Every time we set a color in our CSS, there are really two colors at play: what the browser renders, and what the person sees.

This is sometimes because the browser doesn’t take opacity into account when measuring the contrast ratio.

The contrast ratio tool also doesn't always show in Chrome, often for unclear reasons. If you experience this problem, there is an alternative contrast tool in Firefox as well as other tools.

Colour Contrast Analyzer (CCA)

One of my favorite tools for testing color contrast ratios is the Colour Contrast Analyzer (CCA) desktop application, available for both Mac and Windows.

The app features a color picker that floats above all of your desktop windows, allowing you to sample colors from any application or file type including PDFs.

To use CCA, click the dropper button for either the foreground or background color, then sample your color. When selecting a color from text, choose the center instead of any lighter pixels that may show up as a result of anti-aliasing.

🛠 Challenge: Fix MegaNav Contrast Issues

Update the MegaNav button text color in _header.scss to meet an accessible contrast ratio.

Note that all of the color variables are available inside of _variables.scss.

🛠 Solution: Updating MegaNav Contrast issues

Inside of the _header.scss the very first rule sets the color for the header, which cascades down to navigation menu items:

#header {
    color: var(--color-accent-mediumdark);
    padding-top: 1em;
    position: relative;
}
#header {
    color: var(--color-accent-mediumdark);
    padding-top: 1em;
    position: relative;
}

Changing the accent from mediumdark to just regular dark will set a new color:

#header {
    color: var(--color-accent-dark);
    padding-top: 1em;
    position: relative;
}
#header {
    color: var(--color-accent-dark);
    padding-top: 1em;
    position: relative;
}
